[The state of Colorado can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2763100,209. A county map can be seen at http://geology.com/county-map/colorado-county-map.gif. - Sr.Tech.Ed.MJ

The manifestations of tularemia are not specifically stated. Tularemia is not a very common infection in the USA and much less common in infants because they are usually not in circumstances where they would be exposed. Deer fly or tick-associated transmission is most likely in this infant. Although rashes, other than ulcers at the inoculation site, are not common, another report of tularemia in an infant described a vesicular rash (Byington CL, Bender JM, Ampofo K, et al: Tularemia with vesicular skin lesions may be mistaken for infection with herpes viruses. Clin Infect Dis 2008; 47(1): e4-e6; http://cid.oxfordjournals.org/content/47/1/e4.long). The authors point out that in Edward Francis' original description of the disease, he described a vesicular rash in one person and other studies have also reported rashes, including some with a vesicular component. - Mod.LL]
